    <text>
        <body>
            <p>
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt">A large-scale historical corpus annotated with word sense tags is invaluable for the study of classical texts, especially when morphological analysis is incomplete or unreliable. This is essential for historical language research, where no native speakers can confirm intended meanings. However, manual word sense annotation is particularly challenging in classical languages, requiring expert interpretation of nuanced context. To address this, we developed a system that automatically assigns word sense tags to every content word in a 20-million-word corpus of historical Japanese. Our method uses a Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT) based model (Devlin et al. 2019) and achieves an accuracy of 88.57%. The system operates on tokenized input and directly labels sub-word tokens, avoiding reliance on detailed morphological annotation—making it suitable for diachronic corpus construction where annotation standards may vary over time..</hi>
            </p>
            <p>Data</p>
            <p>
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve">The corpus used in this study is the </hi>
                <hi rend="italic color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt">Corpus of Historical Japanese (CHJ)</hi>
                <hi style="font-size:10pt">(NINJAL, Japan. 2022)</hi>
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve">. Portions of CHJ have been manually annotated with word senses, known as CHJ-WLSP </hi>
                <hi style="font-size:10pt">(Asahara et al. 2022)</hi>
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve">. For word sense tags, we utilized concept IDs provided by the </hi>
                <hi rend="italic color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt">Word List by Semantic Principles (WLSP)</hi>
                <hi style="font-size:10pt">(NINJAL, Japan. 2004)</hi>
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve">, a comprehensive Japanese thesaurus containing 98,214 entries categorized by syntactic and hierarchical semantic principles. concept ID is represented by a five-digit number. For example, concept ID 1.1920 represents “Nominal - relation - quantity - degree/limit.“ This concept ID is used as a word sense tag. Additionally, the historical version of the WLSP, known as the </hi>
                <hi rend="italic color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt">Nihon Koten Taisho Bunrui Goihyo</hi>
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve"> (hWLSP) (Miyajima et al. 2014), includes a thesaurus based on historical word senses, aligned with the vocabulary of the period. Together, these two resources integrate contemporary and historical vocabulary under a unified word sense hierarchy.</hi>
            </p>
            <p>
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve">Table 1 provides an overview of CHJ’s statistics, while Table 2 presents details of CHJ-WLSP (Asada et al. 2023). The CHJ corpus consists of 110 document files, and CHJ-WLSP comprises ten specific works, listed in Table 3 </hi>
                <hi style="font-size:10pt">(Asahara et al. 2022)</hi>
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt">.</hi>
            </p>
