                    <cell style="text-align: right;">3.24</cell>
                </row>
            </table>
            <p>Evaluation</p>
            <p>
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt" xml:space="preserve">We developed two models: one trained exclusively on CHJ-WLSP and the other using both CHJ-WLSP and BCCWJ-WLSP as training data. For validation, we used 1/5 of CHJ-WLSP, with the remaining portion dedicated to training. The approach adopted here follows that proposed in (Asada et al. 2023), employing a sequential labeling method that incorporates document IDs. We believe that document information helps reduce the impact of data diversity. While the entire CHJ corpus serves as our target, we evaluated the model using CHJ-WLSP for validation, as it represents the annotated segment of CHJ. Notably, the definitions of morphological information between CHJ and CHJ-WLSP differ, as morphological definitions have evolved post-annotation of CHJ-WLSP. However, BERT-based models operate without detailed morphological information, allowing accurate prediction of word sense tags. Since both CHJ and BCCWJ were manually tokenized, tokenized sentences were used as input; the BERT tokenizer then segmented them further, with word senses assigned to each sub-word unit. We used </hi>https://huggingface.co/cl-tohoku/bert-base-japanese-v2
                <hi rend="color(222222)" style="font-size:10pt">. The results trained with BERT were better than those trained with RoBERTa.</hi>
            </p>
            <p>Table 5 presents the accuracy scores on the validation set, where a model trained on both CHJ-WLSP and BCCWJ-WLSP achieved an accuracy of 88.57%. For both models, the optimal learning rate was 1e-05, with an epoch count of 15. Accuracy was calculated as the proportion of correctly tagged word senses out of the total number of polysemous words. Notably, the number of target polysemous words increased when BCCWJ-WLSP was included in the training data alongside CHJ-WLSP, enhancing the model’s generalization. Given our aim to annotate the full CHJ corpus, we selected the model trained with both corpora to accommodate potential out-of-vocabulary words from CHJ-WLSP present in the newer CHJ dataset. </p>
